

🚀 Task 1: Fork and Clone the Repository

*Goal:* Create your own copy of the project on GitHub and bring it to your local machine.
1. Fork: Go to the target repository on GitHub and click the *Fork* button (top right). This creates a copy under your username.
2. Clone: Open your terminal and run:
```bash
git clone https://github.com/<your-username>/90DaysOfDevOps.git
cd 2025/git/01_Git_and_Github_Basics

```
Note: Replace `<your-username>` with your actual GitHub handle.

---

📁 Task 2: Initialize and Create a File

Goal: Practice starting a Git project from scratch locally.
1. Create Directory:
```bash
mkdir week-4-challenge
cd week-4-challenge
```
2. Initialize Git: This creates a hidden `.git` folder that tracks your changes.
```bash
git init
```
3. Create File:
```bash
echo "Name: [Your Name] | Role: DevOps Learner" > info.txt
```
4. Stage & Commit: Staging is like putting items in a box; committing is sealing the box and labeling it.
```bash
git add info.txt
git commit -m "Initial commit: Add info.txt with introductory content"
```

🔑 Task 3: Configure Remote & Push (HTTPS/PAT)

Goal: Connect your local folder to your GitHub repository using a Personal Access Token.

1. Generate PAT: Go to GitHub Settings > Developer Settings > Personal Access Tokens (classic). Generate one with `repo` permissions.
2. Set Remote URL:
```bash
git remote add origin https://<your-username>:<your-PAT>@github.com/<your-username>/90DaysOfDevOps.git
```
3. Push: Send your local code to GitHub.
```bash
git push -u origin main
```

